---
interface Props {
  manifest: any;
  formatNum: (n: number) => string;
}

const { manifest: m, formatNum } = Astro.props;
---

<div class="chart-container" id="about">
  <h2 style="font-size:1.3rem; margin-bottom:1rem; color:var(--text);">About This Project</h2>
  <div class="about-text">
    <p>
      In 2018, Ukraine's Ministry of Foreign Affairs launched #KyivNotKiev — a campaign
      to change how the world spells Ukrainian place names. We built a data pipeline to
      measure whether it actually worked.
    </p>
    <p>
      This dashboard tracks {m.analyzable_pairs} Ukrainian toponym pairs (from city names to dishes to
      historical terms) across {m.num_sources} independent data sources. Every data point comes from
      real-world usage — news articles, social media posts, encyclopedia pageviews, book
      frequency, and web search trends.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our computational linguistics layer goes deeper: using transformer models fine-tuned
      on {formatNum(m.cl_corpus)} labeled texts, we classify the <em>context</em> in which each spelling appears.
      The published model and dataset are available on Hugging Face for other researchers
      studying language policy adoption worldwide.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some findings: social media communities adopted Ukrainian spellings 5-9x faster
      than traditional media. "Disaster brands" like Chernobyl are nearly immovable.
      Historical identity terms (Vladimir the Great vs. Volodymyr) barely budged at under 5%.
      And food terms like Borshch are fighting a separate battle, championed by chef
      Yevhen Klopotenko's UNESCO campaign.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="about-links">
    <a href="https://github.com/IvanDobrovolsky/kyivnotkiev">Source Code</a>
    <a href="https://huggingface.co/KyivNotKiev">Hugging Face</a>
  </div>
</div>
